The paper deals with graph theory and its relation to planar graphs, which falls under computational geometry (cs.CG). The paper also discusses the properties of various graph classes, such as quasi-planar graphs and 1-planar graphs, which are related to discrete mathematics (cs.DM) and graph theory (cs.GT). The use of upward digraphs also suggests a connection to data structures (cs.DS). Finally, the paper explores the practical applications of these graph classes, which could fall under social and information networks (cs.SI).
